english:
  title: Dedication Address for the Ridge-Pole of Bojeong Gate
  author: Lee Baek-soon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The tiger crouches and the dragon coils—how magnificent the bearing of our capital! The pheasant soars and the bird spreads its wings—how grand the countenance of this gateway! Four directions gaze upon it; a hundred ages shall take it as their model. What a blessed occasion that this glorious work falls within our flourishing time.

    Once did Gyerim fade beneath autumn's withering leaves, while Gogryeong revealed the verdant pines of renewal. When Heaven sent down its son, the Great Founder laid his foundation. Following the dragon's flight of Hae and Yi through the creative force, he established his dynasty and spread his line. Emulating the turtle of Zhou's wisdom consuming the sacred waters, he raised his state and established his capital. The structure of his dwelling borrowed from the Song of Sigan; the dual gates drew their principle from the hexagram of Ye. Thus were inner and outer made distinct, and the flow of all comings and goings secured—a necessity no hundred sovereigns have forgone, not for a single day.

    Yet ages have passed. Why should not the old be renewed? Our Lord and sovereign embodies the filial piety of Shun and the benevolence of Yao, carries the vision of King Wen and the martial glory of King Wu. He gathers the fallen ways of a thousand years past and spreads his grand designs beyond the three kingdoms of old. With both fortification and cultivation, the master craftsmen direct their plumb-lines and the stone-workers wield their axes. As they raise the pillars, it is as though Nüwa herself sets down the legs of the great tortoise to bear up heaven; as they lift the beams, it is as though the five titans drag the rainbow's tail to mount the Milky Way. The great work nears completion; auspicious blessings descend in abundance.

    Now we dare raise our voices in seven praises and humbly offer our hymns to all six directions:

    Young men, strike the eastern beam! All voices declare the autumn sky unbroken as an eternal rainbow. The sacred virtue spreads boundless as sky and earth, while the sovereign's luminous gaze rests steady as sun and moon.

    Young men, strike the western beam! Four pillars uphold the heavens, making even Huashan bow low. The Queen Mother's jade rings shall pass within these gates, rendering distant tributes unnecessary.

    Young men, strike the southern beam! Auspicious vapors gather and cloud, bringing forth peaches that ripen but once in a thousand years—two offered now, their sweet cry heard thrice in jubilation.

    Young men, strike the northern beam! The four borders know peace; the war drums sound no more. Gold and jade ring out as countless officials gather; treasures sail across the seas as ten thousand lands come in homage.

    Young men, strike the upper beam! Heaven's three stars align in perfect order. Ten thousand people close their doors in peaceful slumber, finding in this work of man the very image of perfect peace.

    Young men, strike the lower beam! We need not envy the grand odes of old, for our realm now equals the Middle Kingdom itself. May this endure ten thousand, ten thousand years to preserve our line.

    After this beam is raised, we humbly pray: May the dragon's blueprint endure forever, and the phoenix calendar extend without limit. Let the immortals of stone and silk-threads pale before our sovereign's span of years, and let even heaven's widest parchment prove insufficient to inscribe his merits. May civil and military virtue accord like zither and flute; may rulers and subjects respond like drum and drumstick. Let nothing fall from its proper place—water, fire, earth, and grain flourish in their seasons; let yin and yang achieve perfect balance—rain and sunshine, heat and cold arrive in their due time. Let wolf-fire smolder at the northern frontier and whale-waves rest in the eastern sea. Let the aged know not of warfare, and children need not learn of suffering. May all people dwell in peace and the realm in quietude.

    So shall our sovereign live ten thousand, ten thousand years.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gyerim (鷄林) and Gogryeong (鵠嶺) are poetic names for Korea and its mountains, with autumn leaves representing the old order and verdant pines the new dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Hae and Yi (羲易) invokes the legendary origins of civilizations and the cosmological order underlying legitimate rulership.
  - key: ''
    value: The comparisons to Nüwa and the five titans (五丁) draw upon classic Chinese mythology to elevate the architectural achievement.
  - key: ''
    value: The refrain 'Young men, strike the beam' (兒郞偉拋梁) represents the ceremonial striking of the ridge-pole during construction, a traditional practice meant to invoke blessings.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three directions' and directional imagery follow traditional cosmological symbolism wherein the ruler occupies the center and radiates virtue to all quarters.
